The paper deals with game theory and mechanism design in the context of online markets, which are central topics in computer science. The use of combinatorial preferences and the analysis of equilibria suggest that the paper belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The mention of crowd sourcing and automatic pricing suggests that Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.MA) are also relevant sub-categories. The study of subsets of products as substitutes or complements suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the exploration of natural generalizations suggests that the paper may also belong to the Electronic Commerce (cs.EC) sub-category.
